tspan.tspan: Figure 2A.
Frequency-current (FI) curves for LIF and QIF
neurons
FI curves for LIF neurons with resting
potentials Vr = -17.0 mV (orange solid line) and Vr = -12.3 mV (red solid line), and QIF neuron (blue solid
line). Dashed lines represent linear fits to the data in the range 1-4 nA, with corresponding gain values
indicated in the legend. The LIF neuron with Vr = -12.3 mV exhibits a gain (10.76 0.26 Hz/nA) most
similar to that of the QIF model (10.74 0.30 Hz/nA), while the LIF neuron with Vr = -17.0 mV (gain =
8.21 0.25 Hz/nA) shows the closest overlap with the QIF curve in the analyzed current range.

text.tspan: Figure 2B. Participation ratio as a function of recurrent connectivity strength. Participation ratio (Dpr/N)
for recurrent neural networks composed of LIF or QIF neurons as a function of the recurrent connectivity
strength R. Synaptic weights are sampled from a normal distribution with zero mean and variance R/N.
Circles represent mean values over 20 independent simulations for networks with different gain values:
LIF neurons with gain = 10.76 0.26 Hz/nA (red), LIF neurons with gain = 8.21 0.25 Hz/nA (orange),
and QIF neurons with gain = 10.74 0.30 Hz/nA (blue). Error bars represent the standard deviation
across simulations. Dashed lines correspond to theoretical fits using the formula Dpr/N = (1 + (R/r)),
with the fitted critical connectivity strength r indicated in the legend for each neuron type.
Figure 2C. Inverse critical connectivity strength as a function of neural gain. The inverse of the critical
connectivity strength (1/r) is plotted against the gain for networks composed of LIF neurons with
different resting potentials (red circles) and QIF neurons (blue circle). Each data point represents the
mean r value obtained from fits to 20 independent simulations, with error bars indicating the standard
deviation. The data points follow a linear relationship (R = 0.988), as predicted theoretically, with the
black dashed line representing the linear fit..

tspan.tspan: Figures 2D and E. Participation ratio in heterogeneous networks with mixed neuron populations.
Participation ratio (Dpr/N) as a function of recurrent connectivity strength R for networks with different
proportions of QIF neurons (pQIF), mixed with LIF neurons. Panel D shows networks with LIF gain =
10.76 Hz/nA, while Panel E shows networks with LIF gain = 8.21 Hz/nA. Different colors represent
varying mixing proportions. In the low connectivity regime (R < 1), heterogeneous networks
(intermediate pQIF values) exhibit systematically lower participation ratios compared to homogeneous
networks, indicating reduced dimensionality when neuron types are mixed.
Figure 2F. Decomposition of participation ratio components in heterogeneous networks.
Analysis of the
terms contributing to the participation ratio according to Eq. (X), shown for two connectivity regimes: low
connectivity (R = 0.1, top panel) and high connectivity (R = 25, bottom panel). The figure displays how
three key statistical measures vary as a function of the mixing proportion pQIF: (i) the auto-covariance
ratio v =
a/, where is the mean auto-covariance across neurons and
a is its standard deviation; (ii)
the mean cross-covariance ratio m = c/, where c is the average of all pairwise cross-covariances; and (iii)
the cross-covariance variability ratio s =
c/, where
c is the standard deviation of all pairwise cross-
covariances. At low connectivity (R = 0.1), heterogeneous networks (intermediate pQIF values) exhibit
increased variability in auto-covariances (higher v), which according to Eq. (X) leads to the observed
reduction in dimensionality. At high connectivity (R = 25),all statistical measures remain relatively
constant across different mixing proportions, consistent with the similar participation ratios observed
across all pQIF values in this regime.
